This means Kenya will not open its borders yet for duty-free entry of sugar as the country seeks to position production to a competitive level.
While consumers are less concerned, and probably can’t tell the difference between local and imported sugar – their main concern being affordability and availability – cane growers, processors, researchers and industry analysts have asked one question; when will the sector be ready to compete?



